(44, 19, 32, 40, 11, 7, 9, 'the assembly was confused', 'Confusion and Expectation', 'This connection highlights the theme of confusion among crowds. In Acts, the assembly is described as ''confused,'' while in Matthew, Jesus questions the motivations of the crowd, suggesting a lack of clarity in their expectations.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 32, 42, 7, 24, 26, 'the assembly was confused', 'Confusion and Inquiry', 'This connection highlights the theme of confusion and inquiry present in both passages. In Acts, the assembly is confused about their purpose, while in Luke, the people are prompted to reflect on their motivations for seeking John the Baptist.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 32, 44, 19, 29, 29, 'the assembly was confused', 'Confusion in the Assembly', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of confusion within the assembly. In Acts 19:29, the city is described as ''filled with confusion,'' which leads to the chaotic events in Acts 19:32 where the assembly is noted as ''confused.''', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 32, 44, 19, 40, 40, 'the assembly was confused', 'Confusion and Uproar Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the confusion and uproar among the assembly. The ''concourse'' in Acts 19:40 reflects the chaotic gathering described in Acts 19:32.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 33, 44, 12, 17, 17, 'beckoned with the hand', 'Use of Beckoning Gesture', 'Both passages emphasize the act of beckoning with the hand to communicate with a crowd. This gesture serves as a means of gaining attention and conveying important messages in both contexts.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 33, 54, 1, 20, 20, 'Alexander', 'Connection of Alexander in Scripture', 'This connection highlights the mention of Alexander in both passages, suggesting a continuity in his role within the early church. Both passages emphasize the consequences of blasphemy and the need for defense against it.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 33, 55, 4, 14, 14, 'Alexander', 'Connection of Alexander References', 'This connection highlights the mention of Alexander in both passages, suggesting a link between his actions in Acts and the harm he caused in 2 Timothy. Both passages emphasize the negative impact of Alexander''s influence.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 33, 42, 1, 22, 22, 'beckoned with the hand', 'Beckoning and Speechlessness', 'Both passages emphasize the act of beckoning, indicating a desire to communicate. In Acts, Alexander beckons to defend himself, while in Luke, the priest beckons but remains speechless.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 33, 44, 13, 16, 16, 'beckoned with the hand', 'Use of Hand Gestures', 'This connection highlights the act of beckoning with the hand in both passages. Both Alexander and Paul use this gesture to gain the attention of the crowd, emphasizing their desire to communicate.', 'parallel', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 33, 50, 1, 7, 7, 'defence', 'Defense of the Gospel', 'This connection highlights the theme of ''defence'' in both passages. In Acts, Alexander seeks to make a defence, while in Philippians, Paul speaks of his own defence of the gospel.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 34, 44, 19, 28, 28, 'Great is Diana of the Ephesians', 'Crying Out for Diana', 'Both passages emphasize the crowd''s unified outcry, declaring, ''Great is Diana of the Ephesians.'' This connection highlights the intensity of the mob''s reaction against Paul and their devotion to Diana.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 34, 40, 6, 7, 7, NULL, 'Repetition in Worship Contexts', 'This connection highlights the theme of repetition in worship, as seen in both passages. Acts 19:34 describes a prolonged chant of ''Great is Diana,'' while Matthew 6:7 warns against ''vain repetitions'' in prayer.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 34, 44, 16, 20, 20, NULL, 'Opposition to Jewish Presence', 'Both passages emphasize the negative reaction to Jews in the cities. In Acts 19:34, the crowd''s outcry is directed against Paul as a Jew, while in Acts 16:20, the accusation against Paul and Silas highlights their Jewish identity as a source of trouble.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 34, 66, 13, 4, 4, 'Great is Diana of the Ephesians', 'Worship and Idolatry Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of worship in both passages. In Acts, the crowd worships Diana, while in Revelation, the worship is directed towards the beast and the dragon.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 34, 11, 18, 26, 26, 'Great is Diana of the Ephesians', 'Worship of False Gods', 'This connection highlights the communal fervor in worshiping false deities. Both passages depict groups calling out to their gods, emphasizing the intensity of their devotion despite the lack of response.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 34, 45, 2, 22, 22, NULL, 'Idolatry and Moral Accountability', 'This connection highlights the theme of idolatry present in both passages. Acts 19:34 references the worship of Diana, while Romans 2:22 addresses the abomination of idols, linking the condemnation of idolatry to moral behavior.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 35, 53, 2, 10, 11, 'worshipper of the great goddess Diana', 'Worship and Deception Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of worship and belief in falsehood. In Acts, the people are devoted to the goddess Diana, while in 2 Thessalonians, there is a warning about believing a lie due to a lack of love for the truth.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 35, 44, 14, 12, 13, 'the image which fell down from Jupiter', 'Worship of Pagan Deities', 'Both passages emphasize the worship of pagan gods, specifically mentioning Jupiter. The connection highlights the cultural significance of these deities in the cities of Ephesus and Lystra.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 35, 49, 2, 12, 12, NULL, 'Connection of Worship and Alienation', 'This connection highlights the contrast between the worship of the goddess Diana in Ephesus and the spiritual state of being ''without God in the world'' as described in Ephesians. Both passages emphasize the significance of divine relationship and the consequences of idolatry.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 35, 54, 4, 2, 2, 'worshipper of the great goddess Diana', 'Conscience and Idolatry Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of idolatry and its impact on moral integrity. The worship of the great goddess Diana in Ephesus may lead to a seared conscience, as indicated in 1 Timothy 4:2.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 35, 44, 18, 19, 19, 'Ephesus', 'Connection to Ephesus', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of Ephesus. Acts 19:35 highlights the city''s worship of Diana, while Acts 18:19 notes Paul''s arrival in Ephesus, indicating its importance in early Christian missions.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 36, 20, 14, 29, 29, 'do nothing rashly', 'Connection of Caution and Understanding', 'This connection highlights the importance of being slow to act and think carefully before responding. Both passages emphasize the value of restraint and understanding over rashness and folly.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 36, 20, 25, 8, 8, 'do nothing rashly', 'Caution Against Rash Actions', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of restraint and caution in decision-making. Acts 19:36 advises against rash actions, while Proverbs 25:8 warns against hastily striving, suggesting that both advocate for thoughtful consideration before acting.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 36, 44, 5, 35, 39, 'do nothing rashly', 'Caution Against Rash Actions', 'This connection highlights the theme of caution in decision-making regarding influential figures. Both passages emphasize the importance of restraint and careful consideration before acting rashly against those perceived as threats.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 37, 45, 2, 22, 22, NULL, 'Idolatry and Moral Accountability', 'Both passages emphasize the condemnation of idolatry and moral hypocrisy. Acts 19:37 addresses the false accusations against Paul and his companions regarding idolatry, while Romans 2:22 questions the moral integrity of those who abhor idols yet commit sacrilege.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 37, 47, 6, 3, 3, NULL, 'Ministry and Offense Connection', 'This connection highlights the importance of maintaining integrity in ministry. Both passages emphasize avoiding actions that could lead to blame or offense.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 37, 44, 25, 8, 8, NULL, 'Defense Against Accusations', 'Both passages emphasize the innocence of the accused. Acts 19:37 mentions that the men are not blasphemers, while Acts 25:8 states that the speaker has not offended against the law or temple.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 37, 46, 10, 32, 32, NULL, 'Offense and Community Relations', 'This connection highlights the importance of not causing offense to different groups, as seen in both passages. Acts 19:37 addresses the defense of individuals against accusations, while 1 Corinthians 10:32 emphasizes avoiding offense to Jews, Gentiles, and the church.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 38, 44, 13, 7, 7, 'deputies', 'Legal Authority and Governance', 'This connection highlights the theme of legal authority in both passages. In Acts 19:38, the mention of ''deputies'' relates to the governance context in Acts 13:7, where Sergius Paulus, a deputy, seeks to hear the word of God.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
